04634nam a22006135i 9780271072470DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211991pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710724707 a10.1515/97802710724702doi  a(DE-B1597)584074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0410002bisacsh04a3012201 aRhoads, John Kenneth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCritical Issues in Social Theory /cJohn Kenneth Rhoads. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: The Scientific Character of Social Theory -- t1. Social Theory According to Positivism -- t2. Social Theory According to Antipositivism -- tPart Two: The Basic Units of Social Theory -- t3. Methodological Structuralism -- t4. Methodological Individualism -- tPart Three. Rules and Social Order -- t5. The Normative Order -- t6. The Construction of Order -- tPart Four: The Duality of Consensus and Conflict -- t7. Consensus -- t8. Conflict -- t9. The Limits of Rationality -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCritical Issues in Social Theory is an analytical survey of persistent controversies that have shaped the field of sociology. It defines, clarifies, and proposes solutions to these ";critical issues"; through commentary on the writings of such influential social theorists as Hobbes, Marx, Durkheim, Weber, Mead, Merton, Parsons, and Schutz.Instead of being just another history, or another classification of theories, Rhoads's four-part model allows him to focus attention on issues that remain at the core of sociological theory today. First, Rhoads analyzes the controversy over positivism as the proper methodological model for the study of human society. Is there one science, of which sociology is a branch, or do the peculiarities of sociology's subject matter require a modification of the scientific method borrowed from the natural sciences? Rhoads next considers the relationship of individuals to society and its structures. Does society have a mode of existence distinct from its members, or is it merely an abstraction derived from the characteristics of individuals? Third, a discussion of social order raises the question of whether social order is the consequence of rules and their underlying moral values, or the product of continuous construction based on self-interest. Finally, the relative importance of consensus and conflict in social relationships is addressed. Is society better understood as a community united by beliefs, values, and rules, or is the social dynamic of continual conflict over beliefs, values, and rules more fundamental? In coming to grips with these issues, the author in some instances takes sides and in others arrives at a synthesis of diverse perspectives. In the final chapter he points to the limitations on the possibility of rational action that come to light in the clashes over these basic issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271072470zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271072470.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE